1. An HTTP service that acts as a policy gate in front of a backend. Three routes by URL prefix: requests under "/api/v1/" go through the policy check; requests starting with "/health" return 200 immediately for liveness; anything else returns 404. Two policy gates apply to the "/api/v1/" route: the URL path must not exceed a maximum length loaded from a file at startup, and the request method must equal the allowed method also loaded from a file. Failures return 403 with a body explaining which gate refused. Every single request is recorded as a single JSON line in an audit file with method, path, status, and Unix-epoch timestamp; user-controlled fields are JSON-escaped so a path containing a quote cannot break the line. The audit log is fail-closed: if the file cannot be opened or written, the binary aborts before producing a response, so the operator never sees a served request that wasn't audited. Concurrency is fork-per-accept; the policy files are read once by the parent at startup and inherited by each worker via copy-on-write.
